This annual report is one\nmeans of documenting these relationships. Information contained in\nthis document is designed to serve several purposes and a wide range\nof audiences from private individuals to NASA employees, but the\nemphasis is on NASA\'s sponsored efforts rather than on fiscal data.\nIt is noted, however, that $115 million was obligated during FY 73\nfor work in 280 institutions on some 2600 projects. A "User\'sGuide"\nis included to facilitate fullest use of the material related to the\ninterests of any particular reader.\n\nInformation on obtaining reports resulting from these projects may be\nobtained from: NASA, Scientific and Technical Information Office,\nCode KS, Washington, D. C. 20546.\n\nAny comments or inquiries regarding this document should be\ndirected to:\nChief, Coordination Branch\nOffice of University Affairs, Code PY\nNational Aeronautics and Space Administration\nWashington, D.C. 20546\n\nTABLE OF CONTENTS\nThis report includesdataon projects active during Fiscal Year 1973.\n\nPage\nAlabama ..................................... 1\nAlaska CASE Fields of Science and Engineering\nThe National Science Foundation (NSF) on behalf of the Committee\non Academic Science and Engineering (CASE) of the Federal Council\nfor Science and Technology (FCST) operates a government-wide\nsystem for collecting and analyzing data on support to colleges and\nuniversities. Participating agencies report annually to NSF which i n\nturn issues Support to U~riversities, Col1ege.r a~ld Selected No~rprofit\nI~rstitutio~rs.\nThe CASE Fields, used in the extensive tabulations\ncontained in that document, form the only consistent classification\nsystem for government sponsored research. The fields are listed in full\nin Appendix B.\n\nIV. Cross-Indexes\nThe cross-indexed Appendices are related to the citations by the\naccession number (item 3). The accession number has meaning only\nin this report; it is in no way premanently associated with,nor doesit\nuniquely identify a grant o r contract anywhere except in,the present\nreport.\nAppendix A - Given only the grant o r contract number this index\nenables the reader to locate the citation. The first\npage tells how to distinguish grants from contracts.\nAppendix B - This index provides rapid access to all projects in a\nparticular area of endeavor, as defined by the CASE\nFields. The listing is also easily used to determine the\ninstitutions and principal investigators c o n d u c t i n g\nNASA projects in a field.\nAppendix C - T h e types of effort sponsored by each NASA\ninstallation may be determined from this index.\n~ ~ ~ e n D- iThis index is included primarily for the convenience of\nd x\ninternal NASA readers. However, the RTOP, per se,\nmay be of considerable interest to external users. See\nV, below.\n\nV. Source Code and RTOP\nThe last line of the citation (item 1 I) contains 1-3 sets of numbers in\nparenthesis. By interpreting the coding a great deal of additional\ninformation on a project may be obtained. The first set is current and\nis the most useful; the second and third sets, if present, generally\nrepresent historical data.\n\nEach set of numbers is further divided into two groups separated by\na blank space. The first group contains source coding, while the\nsecond is the "Research and Technology Operating Plan" (RTOP).\nSource Coding (Item 1la)\nThe first two-digit number identifies the NASA installation\n(by the code given in 11, above) which has most recently\nadded funds to the project. Disagreement between this\ninstallation and the technical officer location usually indicates\nthat responsibility for a project is being transferred.\n\nThe second number identifies the major NASA Program\nOffice responsible for the research, as follows: 200-299,\nOffice of T e c h n o l o g y Utilization; 300-399, Office of\nUniversity Affairs; 500-599, Office of Tracking and Data\nAcquisition; 600-699, Office of Applications; 700-799, Office\nof Aeronautics and Space Technology; 800-899, Office of\nSpace Science; and 900-999, Office of Manned Space Flight.\n\nRTOP (Item 1 lb)\nThe RTOP, "Research and Technology Operating Plan"\nnumber indicates a broad technical area in which NASA\ndesires to achieve certain objectives. Numerous projects,\nconducted both in-house and out-of-house and with all\nclasses of performers may contribute to the objective of a\nsingle RTOP. Detailed descriptions of the RTOPs, including\nnames of responsible individuals and extensive cross-indexing\nare published annually. The current edition entitled Research\nand Techtro1og.v Operatitig Plat1 Summary may be purchased\nfrom the National Technical Information Service (NTIS),\nSpringfield, Virginia 22151, for $3.00. ($2.50 additional for\nForeign mailing.)\n\nvii\n\nNASA\'s UNIVERSITY PROGRAM\n\nNGR OI-WI-021\nAlabama A&M University\nPerformance analysis & preliminary system configuration\n\nALABAMA\n\nPcnd\n\nNGR OI-001-OW\nAlabama A&M Unirerrity\n1WO\nComputer code for predicting neutron reaction cross actions and\ngamma ray spectrum in certain radiation shielding materials as\nwell as in nitrogen & oxygen\n\n03/05/73-M/30/74\n. .\nPlr,,. lnwrr.\n\nWeathers, G . Abbreviations used for locations are: ARC,\nAmes Research Center; FRC, Flight Research Center; GSFC, Goddard\nSpace Flight Center; KSC, Kennedy Space Center, JSC, Johnson Space\nCenter; LARC, Langley Research Center; .LERC, Lewis Research Center;\nMSFC, Marshall Space Flight Center; WS, Wallops Station and HQ,\nHeadquarters. The HQ designator carries suffixed letters identifying individual\nHeadquarters offices; an explanation of these identificrs and full addresses\nfor all installations may be found i n the prefatory pages.
